Jocelyn,

I was able to implement your cti file, and the reaction rates are
applied to the gas phase, but are indeed very small (on the order of
1e-27).  

The one thing I did notice is that your activation energy is listed
as 40,000 cal/mol, which translates to 1.67e8 J/kmol.  If you&#39;re
leaving the Tin at 300 K in the &#39;difflame.m&#39; code, this means that
the exponential term in the reaction rate:

 exp(-Eact/RT)

is equal to ~ 6.94e-30, which would definitely explain the reaction&#39;s
lack of impact on the overal state of the gas.  As is, this reaction
would only show appreciable progress at considerably higher T. 
Either changing the units line or decreasing the activation energy
would make this reaction proceed faster at a lower T.

Hope this helps,
Steven



